\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Definition of Service Quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department operates as a compliance-enforcement and technology governance function within Elko County.
 The Department's mandate is to establish,
 maintain,
 and enforce compliance with information and technology standards,
 and to bring non-compliant systems and practices into alignment with those standards.
 It does not operate as a hospitality or satisfaction-driven service organization,
 and end-user satisfaction with the outcome of a compliance decision does not constitute a measure of service quality under this mandate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Service quality is defined by accuracy,
 auditability,
 and adherence to policy.
 A technician who brings a non-compliant system into compliance clearly,
 professionally,
 and in accordance with the communication standards defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 has delivered service of the highest quality,
 regardless of whether the end user found the outcome convenient or welcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director is accountable to the County Manager for the performance and conduct of the Department.
 Department heads and end users are not the Department's managerial authority,
 and their dissatisfaction with a technically correct and professionally executed compliance action does not constitute grounds for corrective action against IT personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Authorized Feedback Channels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department does not operate passive feedback collection mechanisms such as satisfaction surveys,
 open feedback forms,
 or suggestion systems.
 End-user satisfaction with compliance outcomes is not an operational input to technical standards or service delivery decisions,
 and passive feedback mechanisms of this type do not produce actionable intelligence sufficient to justify the administrative overhead or the implied premise that survey sentiment governs operational direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department accepts feedback through the following authorized channels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
County Manager
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall solicit feedback from the County Manager at each regularly scheduled monthly meeting as a minimum cadence.
 This does not limit communication —
 the County Manager may raise concerns,
 complaints,
 commendations,
 or observations at any time through any channel,
 and the IT Director may likewise bring matters to the County Manager outside the scheduled meeting when circumstances warrant.
 The monthly meeting establishes the routine checkpoint;
 it does not constrain the relationship to that interval.
 The IT Director shall document the substance of any actionable feedback received through this channel in the Department's system of record (Redmine) and shall initiate a response or corrective action as warranted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Work Order System and Written Correspondence
\series default
:
 End users and department heads may provide service-related feedback through the designated work order system (Redmine) or in direct written correspondence addressed to the IT Director.
 IT personnel shall document feedback received informally —
 including verbal complaints and hallway conversations —
 in the relevant work order in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Feedback submitted through the work order system or written correspondence shall be acknowledged by the IT Director or Assistant IT Director within five (5) business days of receipt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT Staff (Upward Feedback)
\series default
:
 IT personnel shall surface operational feedback,
 service delivery concerns,
 and process improvement observations to their direct supervisor or the IT Director through the established chain of command.
 Staff observations have direct operational value as the Department's primary ground-level intelligence on service delivery effectiveness and shall be actively solicited and considered by Department leadership.
 This upward feedback channel is the Department's principal mechanism for identifying process improvements and service delivery gaps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Grievance Pathways
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Service-related grievances —
 defined as formal expressions of dissatisfaction with IT service delivery,
 technical decisions,
 or compliance-enforcement actions —
 shall be routed exclusively through the pathways defined in this section.
 These pathways are the only legitimate channels for service grievances.
 Informal or lateral communications that attempt to circumvent these pathways —
 including direct appeals to County leadership outside the defined chain,
 back-channel pressure on IT staff,
 or misrouting of service disputes into HR processes —
 shall be redirected to the appropriate channel by the receiving party.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Grievance against an IT technician or staff member
\series default
:
 The complainant shall submit the grievance in writing to the IT Director.
 The IT Director shall evaluate the grievance against the compliance record,
 the communication standards in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 and the conduct standards in 
\series bold
Policies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Where the grievance concerns a technically correct and professionally executed compliance action,
 the IT Director shall document the finding,
 close the matter,
 and provide written notification of the disposition to the complainant.
 Where the grievance identifies a legitimate conduct or process deficiency,
 the IT Director shall initiate appropriate corrective action through the Department's internal performance management process.
 Grievance dispositions shall be documented in the Department's system of record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Grievance against the IT Director
\series default
:
 The complainant shall direct the grievance to the County Manager.
 The County Manager serves as the IT Director's administrative authority and is the appropriate party to evaluate complaints about the IT Director's decisions or conduct.
 This pathway shall not be used as a mechanism to compel changes to compliance policy or technical standards;
 such requests remain subject to the risk management process in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 regardless of the channel through which they are raised.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Department head escalation
\series default
:
 Where a department head is unsatisfied with the IT Director's written disposition of a service grievance,
 the department head may escalate the matter to the County Manager.
 This pathway represents the final internal escalation available for service-related disputes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Compliance relaxation requests
\series default
:
 A request by any party to relax,
 waive,
 or deviate from a technical standard or compliance control is not a service grievance and shall not be processed through the pathways defined in this section.
 Such requests shall be directed to the IT Director and processed through the formal risk acceptance process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 This determination applies regardless of how the request is framed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Staff Protection and Performance Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT personnel shall not be subject to negative performance evaluations,
 formal corrective action,
 or adverse informal treatment on the basis of end-user or departmental dissatisfaction with a compliance outcome,
 provided the personnel member acted in accordance with the technical standards of this manual,
 the communication standards of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 and the conduct standards of 
